The app is minimal but has several real issues:

#### 🔴 High Severity

| Issue | Location | Detail |
|---|---|---|
| **No authentication** | `GET /users` | User data (names + emails) is exposed to anyone — no auth middleware, no session check, no API key. |
| **PII exposure** | `GET /users` (line 12–15) | Email addresses are returned to unauthenticated callers. Even with static data, this pattern is dangerous when connected to a real database. |

#### 🟠 Medium Severity

| Issue | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Missing security headers** | No `helmet` middleware — leaves the app open to clickjacking, MIME-sniffing, etc. |
| **No rate limiting** | Both endpoints can be hit unlimited times — trivial to DoS or enumerate. |
| **No HTTPS enforcement** | App binds plaintext HTTP on port 3000 with no redirect or TLS termination at the app layer. |

#### 🟡 Low Severity

| Issue | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No global error handler** | Unhandled errors will leak stack traces to clients in development mode. |
| **Timestamp in `/health`** | Minor info disclosure — reveals server clock skew, useful for timing attacks. |
| **No input validation middleware** | `express.json()` is absent. If POST routes are added later, the app has no body parsing guardrails. |

